WEBVTT

00:01.700 --> 00:04.860
As you all know, at the beginning
of term, the bishop graciously

00:04.900 --> 00:07.700
bestowed a beautiful
piece of religious art

00:07.740 --> 00:10.540
onto our lady immaculate college

00:10.580 --> 00:13.260
the enchanting child of Prague.

00:15.380 --> 00:18.820
Music: Jazzie's groove
by soul ii soul

00:22.620 --> 00:24.140
there we are.

00:24.180 --> 00:25.940
Sure, isn't he
a great fella altogether?

00:25.980 --> 00:27.900
I still don't get what
it's supposed to be.

00:27.940 --> 00:30.100
It's Jesus as a wain.

00:30.140 --> 00:31.660
Why has he got a big red hat on?

00:31.700 --> 00:32.700
Nobody knows.

00:32.740 --> 00:33.980
It was the bishop's wish that

00:34.020 --> 00:36.500
he be passed around all
the schools in the derry diocese.

00:36.540 --> 00:38.180
Therefore we are joined this morning

00:38.220 --> 00:40.140
by mr Malone,
headmaster of st Benedict's,

00:40.180 --> 00:42.300
so that the handover ceremony
can take place.

00:42.340 --> 00:44.380
You're very welcome, mr Malone.

00:44.420 --> 00:47.500
Though I fear you may have had
a wasted journey.

00:47.540 --> 00:51.140
I've thought about it,
and I'd much rather

00:51.180 --> 00:53.820
just hold on to him, actually.

00:53.860 --> 00:55.700
He brightens up my office.

00:55.740 --> 00:57.780
He doesn't answer back.

00:58.980 --> 01:00.460
I like the fella.

01:00.500 --> 01:04.140
And if the bishop has a problem with
that, he can take it up with me.

01:04.180 --> 01:05.860
Now, what else was there?

01:07.060 --> 01:08.260
Yes.

01:08.300 --> 01:12.500
Sadly, sister Patrick
has decided to leave us.

01:12.540 --> 01:14.660
She's returning to
her missionary work,

01:14.700 --> 01:19.780
educating the heathen inhabitants
of a primitive and savage place.

01:19.820 --> 01:22.340
She's...Taken a teaching
post in belfast, sister.

01:22.380 --> 01:23.580
Precisely.

01:23.620 --> 01:25.260
The board of governors promised me

01:25.300 --> 01:27.300
that her replacement
would arrive today,

01:27.340 --> 01:30.380
but as usual
they were talking out of their...

01:30.420 --> 01:31.007
Door bangs

01:31.740 --> 01:33.940
music: I can't be with you
by the Cranberries

01:35.700 --> 01:37.500
I believe you've been expecting me.

01:40.580 --> 01:41.900
Here we go.

01:44.820 --> 01:47.780
Lying in my bed again

01:47.820 --> 01:50.780
and I cry cos you're not here...

01:54.420 --> 01:55.780
Chalk pings and clatters

01:58.860 --> 01:59.860
she sighs

02:05.860 --> 02:08.740
what is it we should be doing, miss?

02:08.780 --> 02:10.539
"What should you be doing?"

02:12.420 --> 02:14.940
Now, there's the question.

02:16.620 --> 02:18.220
But let me ask you a better one.

02:19.940 --> 02:21.220
What is it you want to do?

02:21.260 --> 02:22.740
Get pished.

02:22.780 --> 02:25.540
I'd quite like some feedback on
the poetry assignment, actually.

02:25.580 --> 02:26.860
Dickhead.

02:26.900 --> 02:29.180
It counts towards our
final grade, people!

02:29.220 --> 02:31.140
This is 12a, right?

02:31.180 --> 02:32.380
That is correct, miss.

02:32.420 --> 02:34.740
And you are? Jenny. Jenny Joyce.

02:36.260 --> 02:37.420
Here we go.

02:37.460 --> 02:39.620
The flower, by Jenny Joyce.

02:39.660 --> 02:42.260
You're not going to read it out,
are you? Of course.

02:42.300 --> 02:44.700
Poetry should always be read aloud.

02:46.100 --> 02:49.740
"Some flowers are tall
some flowers are small

02:49.780 --> 02:51.940
"some flowers barely grow at all."

02:53.460 --> 02:55.100
Ok... that's not the end.

02:55.140 --> 02:56.180
It should be.

02:56.220 --> 02:57.780
Here's a poem about a dog.

02:57.820 --> 02:59.500
Here's another one about a dog.

02:59.540 --> 03:01.460
This one has no name on it.

03:01.500 --> 03:03.980
An English rose among thorns?

03:06.340 --> 03:09.860
Yeah, I can see why you might want
to remain anonymous, all right.

03:09.900 --> 03:11.260
Dog poem.

03:11.300 --> 03:13.180
Poem about a tree.

03:13.220 --> 03:15.260
This one's called boys.

03:15.300 --> 03:16.940
"I think boys are really class

03:16.980 --> 03:20.540
"especially the ones
who have a nice ass."

03:20.580 --> 03:21.940
It's called a haiku.

03:21.980 --> 03:23.860
That's not what I would call it.

03:23.900 --> 03:26.180
Dog poem. Dog poem.

03:26.220 --> 03:28.620
Here someone's just
drawn a picture of a dog.

03:30.860 --> 03:33.300
That is not bad, actually.
Thank you very much.

03:33.340 --> 03:37.260
This person has written about how
much they love their English class,

03:37.300 --> 03:40.340
in an embarrassing attempt
to suck up to the teacher.

03:40.380 --> 03:43.220
Dog poem. Dog poem.

03:43.260 --> 03:44.580
Cat poem.

03:44.620 --> 03:45.740
Yes?

03:45.780 --> 03:47.660
I think a lot of people
in this class,

03:47.700 --> 03:49.380
and I know no-one will
mind me saying this,

03:49.420 --> 03:52.780
well, they have a very basic
grasp of the creative process.

03:52.820 --> 03:55.540
Whereas I've been writing for years,
so I'm really not afraid to

03:55.580 --> 03:57.540
put myself out there,

03:57.580 --> 03:59.900
to be bold, to take risks.

03:59.940 --> 04:01.460
And you are?

04:01.500 --> 04:03.420
That's my cousin. Erin Quinn.

04:03.460 --> 04:04.900
Erin Quinn.

04:04.940 --> 04:06.300
Here we go.

04:07.700 --> 04:11.500
"The bullets fired on
the streets as I lie in my bed

04:11.540 --> 04:15.220
"are nothing to
the bullets being fired...

04:15.260 --> 04:16.540
"In my head."

04:16.579 --> 04:19.579
It's about the troubles
in a political sense,

04:19.620 --> 04:23.260
but also about my own troubles,
in a personal sense.

04:23.300 --> 04:25.540
No, I understand the weak analogy.

04:26.740 --> 04:28.380
This isn't bold, Erin.

04:28.420 --> 04:30.340
It's someone failing to be bold.

04:30.380 --> 04:31.780
Well, I'm sorry if the subtleties

04:31.820 --> 04:33.500
of my work were lost on you,
miss de brun.

04:33.540 --> 04:35.340
Poetry is truth.

04:35.380 --> 04:40.660
And great poetry is raw and real
and messy and glorious and ugly.

04:40.700 --> 04:43.100
It is dragged from
the depths of the soul.

04:43.140 --> 04:46.780
It helps us understand
each other and ourselves.

04:46.820 --> 04:49.060
Do you get what I'm saying?

04:49.100 --> 04:50.540
Yes.

04:50.580 --> 04:52.980
Yes, I think I do, actually.

04:53.020 --> 04:54.540
Not a baldies.

04:54.580 --> 04:57.860
It's not often in life
you're allowed to tear up the page

04:57.900 --> 04:59.020
and start over.

05:00.940 --> 05:03.420
But I am gonna give you that chance.

05:05.540 --> 05:06.860
Impress me.

05:06.900 --> 05:08.980
Music: Return to innocence
by enigma

05:15.420 --> 05:16.900
ach, this is lovely, Gerry.

05:16.940 --> 05:19.100
I thought it'd be nice for us
to do something together,

05:19.140 --> 05:20.300
just the two of us, you know?

05:20.340 --> 05:21.820
Mary! Gerry!

05:21.860 --> 05:25.500
You're not allowed to
smoke in this place.

05:25.540 --> 05:28.100
Can you believe that? It's barbaric.

05:28.140 --> 05:30.220
Sarah, what are you doing here?

05:30.260 --> 05:32.340
Mary said you were having
a wee night to yourselves,

05:32.380 --> 05:34.100
so I thought
you might want some company.

05:34.140 --> 05:35.660
Why? W-why would you think that?

05:35.700 --> 05:36.780
Sarah!

05:36.820 --> 05:39.220
Himself as well, is it? Great(!)

05:39.260 --> 05:40.380
Sweet Jesus.

05:40.420 --> 05:42.220
Hiya, how are ye?

05:42.260 --> 05:44.980
They don't let you smoke in here,
ciaran. Can you credit it?

05:45.020 --> 05:46.820
This is a nice surprise.

05:46.860 --> 05:48.460
When Sarah asked me to the cinema,

05:48.500 --> 05:51.140
I thought, well, I thought
she meant just the two of us.

05:51.180 --> 05:55.660
No, ciaran, because that would be...
What's the word now? Normal.

05:55.700 --> 05:57.580
Double date it is, then, so.

05:57.620 --> 05:59.180
Wonder what's keeping daddy.

06:00.980 --> 06:02.900
Excuse me? I've got the tickets.

06:02.940 --> 06:04.940
We haven't decided
what we want to see yet, da!

06:04.980 --> 06:07.660
Well, I liked the look of that one
with all the lads in the line-up.

06:07.700 --> 06:09.780
It's got your man in it,
the farmer from glenroe.

06:09.820 --> 06:11.260
What, Gabriel byrne?

06:11.300 --> 06:13.500
He's done a fair bit
since glenroe now.

06:13.540 --> 06:15.380
Who are you? His agent?

06:15.420 --> 06:18.180
Da, I don't understand this.
You hate the cinema.

06:18.220 --> 06:19.340
Not since I discovered

06:19.380 --> 06:21.460
it's the only way I can spend time
with our colm.

06:21.500 --> 06:24.300
It's the one place
the boring bastard doesn't talk.

06:24.340 --> 06:25.940
But colm's not here, is he, da?

06:27.740 --> 06:29.220
Da?

06:29.260 --> 06:31.980
..And that's not to say, now,
that in my younger years,

06:32.020 --> 06:34.700
I didn't enjoy a boiled sweet.

06:34.740 --> 06:38.060
But then I heard tell
of a fella from ballynahinch...

06:38.100 --> 06:39.940
What was it his name was, now?

06:39.980 --> 06:41.540
I had it there a minute ago.

06:41.580 --> 06:43.020
Ach, it'll come to me.

06:43.060 --> 06:47.580
Anyway, this ballynahinch lad,
and, as I say, his name escapes me,

06:47.620 --> 06:50.260
but he was mad keen on
the boiled sweets.

06:50.300 --> 06:52.940
Sure, he couldn't get
enough of them.

06:52.980 --> 06:56.780
But in the end, well,
didn't he choke to death on one?

06:56.820 --> 07:00.180
A pear drop, I think it was.

07:00.220 --> 07:01.460
Or a clove rock, maybe.

07:01.500 --> 07:04.420
But either way,
it's not how I'd want to go.

07:04.460 --> 07:06.100
I know, love. I know.

